06240nam a22012975i 9780691221588DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20201993nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912215887 a10.1515/97806912215882doi  a(DE-B1597)572694  a(OCoLC)1226679877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a297/.09598/12221 aBowen, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMuslims through Discourse :bReligion and Ritual in Gayo Society /cJohn R. Bowen. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transcription -- tPART ONE: A Genealogy of Divergent Understandings -- tChapter One Introduction -- tChapter Two Religious Disputes in Takèngēn -- tChapter Three Islamic Knowledge in the Highlands, 1900-1990 -- tPART TWO: Powerful Speech and Spirit Transactions -- tChapter Four Spells, Prayer, and the Power of Words -- tChapter Five The Source of Human Powers in History -- tChapter Six The Healer's Struggle -- tChapter Seven Exorcism and Accountability -- tChapter Eight Farming, Ancestors, and the Sacred Landscape -- tChapter Nine Adam and Eve's Children -- tPART THREE Negotiating Public Rituals -- tChapter Ten Transacting through Food: The Kenduri and Its Critics -- tChapter Eleven Speaking for the Dead -- tChapter Twelve Sacrifice, Merit, and Self-Interest -- tChapter Thirteen Worship and Public Life -- tChapter Fourteen The Social Forms of Religious Change -- tGlossary of Gayo and Arabic Terms -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this rich account of a Muslim society in highland Sumatra, Indonesia, John Bowen describes how men and women debate among themselves ideas of what Islam is and should be--as it pertains to all areas of their lives, from work to worship. Whereas many previous anthropological studies have concentrated on the purely local aspects of culture, this book captures and analyzes the tension between the local and universal in everyday life. Current religious differences among the Gayo stem from debates between "traditionalist" and "modernist" scholars that began in the 1930s, and reveal themselves in the ways Gayo discuss and perform worship, sacrifice, healing, and rites of birth and death, all within an Islamic framework. Bowen considers the power these debates accord to language, especially in arguments over spells, rites of farming, hunting, and healing. Moreover, he traces in these debates a general conception of transacting with spirits that has shaped Gayo practices of sacrifice, worship, and aiding the dead. Bowen concludes by examining the development of competing religious ideas in the highlands, the alternative ritual forms and ideas they have pro-mulgated, and the implications of this phenomenon for the emergence of an Islamic public sphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGayo (Indonesian people)xReligious life and customs. 0aIslamzIndonesiazSumatra. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAcehnese language.  aAcehnese.  aAdam.  aAfterbirth.  aAlimin.  aBani, Aman.  aBooks, religious.  aChildren of pious deeds.  aClever Chief.  aCombs-Schilling, Elaine.  aDarul Islam.  aDebates.  aDewi, Aman.  aEducation.  aFaith.  aFasting.  aFunerals.  aGayo region.  aGraham, William.  aHamzah Fansuri.  aHealers.  aHunting.  aIncense.  aIndonesian state.  aIslamicate culture.  aJava.  aJukri, Aman.  aKaro Batak.  aKebayakan.  aLaw, on sorcery.  aLetter symbolism.  aLord of the Fiel